hives|first1=Tennis|title=European Championship 1902|url=http://www.tennisarchives.com/voorloopfiche.php?wedstrijdvoorloopid=1033 |publisher=Tennis Archives |date=2016 |accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n| Hard (i)\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Laurence Doherty]]\n| 4\u20136, 6\u20134, 6\u20133, 6\u20131\n|-\n| 77.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Apr 1903\n| [[British Covered Court Championships]]\n| Hard (i)\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[George Hillyard]]\n| 6\u20133, 7\u20139, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 78.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1903\n| Middlesex Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Brame Hillyard]]\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20132, 6\u20133, 3\u20136, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 79.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jul 1903\n| Berkshire Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} Alfred E. Crawley\n| 6\u20133, 8\u20136\n|-  \n| 80.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1904\n| Middlesex Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} Frederick Payn\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20132, 6\u20134\n|-  \n| 81.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1904\n| [[Kent Championships]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Beckenham Lawn Tennis Club: Kent Championships|url=http://www.beckenhamtennisclub.co.uk/history/kent-all-comers-championships-roll/ |publisher=Beckenham Lawn Tennis Club |date=2016|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Brame Hillyard]]\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20132, 6\u20134\n|-  \n| 82.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jul 1904\n| North London Championships (Gipsy)\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Alfred Beamish]]\n| 6\u20131, 5\u20137, 6\u20132, 6\u20131\n|-\n| 83.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Jul 1904\n| [[Queen's Club Championships|Championship of London]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Josiah Ritchie]]\n| 6\u20133, 7\u20139, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 84.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jul 1904\n| Berkshire Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Walter Crawley]] \n| 5\u20137, 6\u20131, 6\u20134\n|-  \n| 85.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Aug 1904\n| Crystal Palace\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} Ernest Parton \n| 6\u20133, 6\u20132\n|-\n| 86.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Jun 1905\n| [[Kent Championships]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Norman Brookes]]\n| w.o.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Harold Mahony}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{Sports-reference|ma/harold-mahony-1}}\n\n{{Wimbledon men's singles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahony, Harold}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Scottish male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Irish male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medallists for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medallists for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:People from County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Cycling road incident deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon champions (pre-Open Era)]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in tennis]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's singles]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Ireland]]\n[[Category:British male tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British tennis player}}\n{{for|the Australian footballer|Harold Mahony (footballer)}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                              = Harold Mahony\n|image                             = Harold mahony.jpg\n|caption                           =\n|fullname                          = Harold Segerson Mahony\n|country                           = {{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland|United Kingdom]]\n|residence                         =\n|birth_date                        = {{birth date |df=yes|1867|02|13}}\n|birth_place                       = [[Edinburgh]], Scotland, UK\n|death_date                        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1905|06|27|1867|02|13}}\n|death_place                       = [[County Kerry]], Ireland\n|height                            = {{convert|1.91|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|college                           =\n|turnedpro                         = 1890<small> (amateur tour)</small>\n|retired                           = 1905<small> (due to death)</small>\n|plays                             =\n|careerprizemoney                  =\n|tennishofyear                     =\n|tennishofid                       =\n|website                           =\n|singlesrecord                     = \n|singlestitles                     = 59 <ref>{{cite web|title=Harold Segerson Mahony: Stats|url=http://www.tennisarchives.com/player.php?playerid=24 |publisher=Tennis Archives|accessdate=17 August 2016}}</ref>\n|highestsinglesranking             = No. 2 (1896<small>, Karoly Mazak</small>)<ref name=\"Mazak\">Mazak, Karoly (2010). ''The Concise History of Tennis'', p. 24.</ref>\n|currentsinglesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenresult              =\n|FrenchOpenresult                  =\n|Wimbledonresult                   = '''W''' ([[1896 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1896]])\n|USOpenresult                      = 4R ([[1903 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1903]])\n|Othertournaments                  = \n|MastersCupresult                  =\n|Olympicsresult                    =\n|doublesrecord                     =\n|doublestitles                     =\n|highestdoublesranking             =\n|currentdoublesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult       =\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult           =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult            = F ([[1892 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles|1892]], [[1903 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles|1903]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult               = F (1897)\n|OthertournamentsDoubles           = \n|MastersCupDoublesresult           =\n|OlympicsDoublesresult             =\n|Mixed                             = <!-- adds mixed information-->\n|mixedrecord                       =\n|mixedtitles                       =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult         =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult             =\n|WimbledonMixedresult              =\n|USOpenMixedresult                 =\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles      = \n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult         =\n| medaltemplates-expand       = yes\n| medaltemplates              =\n{{MedalCountry | {{GBR}} }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Tennis at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's singles|Singles]]}}\n{{MedalBronze | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Tennis at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's doubles|Doubles]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|a [[Image:Olympic flag.svg|22px]] [[Mixed team at the 1900 Summer Olympics|Mixed team]]}}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1900 Summer Olympics|1900 Paris]] | [[Tennis at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Mixed doubles|Mixed doubles]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Harold Segerson Mahony''' (13 February 1867 \u2013 27 June 1905) was a Scottish-born [[tennis]] player who is best known for winning the singles title at the [[Wimbledon Championships]] in 1896. His career lasted from 1888 until his death in 1905. Mahony was born in Scotland but lived in Ireland for the majority of his life; his family were Irish including both of his parents, the family home was in County Kerry, Southwestern Ireland. He was the last Scottish born man to win Wimbledon until the victory of [[Andy Murray]] at the 2013 championships.<ref>''The Today Programme'', BBC Radio 4, 8 July 2013</ref>\n\n==Career==\nMahony was born at 21 Charlotte Square, Edinburgh to Richard John Mahony, an Irish barrister and prominent landowner. The family had a home in Scotland but spent most of their time at [[Dromore Castle (County Kerry)|Dromore Castle]], in [[County Kerry]], Ireland. Harold trained on a specially built tennis court at Dromore.<ref name=\"Grand Slam Winner\">{{cite news |title=Scotland's only winner of a Grand Slam. So far|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/tennis/scotlands-only-winner-of-a-grand-slam-so-far-1884533.html|newspaper=The Independent |author=David Randall |date=31 January 2010 |accessdate=2 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nMahony made his [[Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon]] debut in 1890 exiting in the first round.<ref name=wimbledon>{{cite web|title=Wimbledon players archive \u2013 Harold Mahony|url=http://www.wimbledon.com/en_GB/scores/draws/archive/players/4ff91993-67cf-494a-b445-4b268c0da35a/index.html|publisher=[[AELTC]]}}</ref> He reached the semifinal in 1891 and 1892.<ref name=\"Grand Slam Winner\"/> Mahony spent some time in America in the mid-1890s, before returning to England and finally taking the Wimbledon crown in 1896. In the final he beat [[Wilfred Baddeley]] of Great Britain in five sets: 6\u20132, 6\u20138, 5\u20137, 8\u20136, 6\u20133.<ref name=\"Grand Slam Winner\"/> Under the challenger system Mahony was entitled to defend the Wimbledon title in 1897 but this time he was beaten in the Challenge Round in three straight sets by [[Reginald Doherty]].<ref name=wimbledon/> He was the last Scottish-born player to win a grand slam until [[Andy Murray]] won the US Open in 2012 and win Wimbledon until Murray won it in 2013. He was recognised as the third and last Irishman to win the Wimbledon singles.<ref> Devastating backhand nets glory for Mahony By Ryle Dwyer, ''The Irish Examiner'', 1 August 2012</ref>\n\nHe won the singles title at the [[British Covered Court Championships]], played at the [[Queen's Club]] in London, in 1893 and successfully defended his title the following year. In 1895 Mahony forfeited the defence of his title due to illness.<ref name=killed>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article87141563 |title=ME. H. S. MAHONY KILLED. |newspaper=Bunbury Herald (WA : 1892 \u2013 1919) |location=WA |date=14 August 1905 |page=1 |publisher=National Library of Australia}}</ref> In 1898 he won the singles titles at the prestigious [[Irish Open (tennis)|Irish Championships]]. That same year Mahony, who was a regular competitor in Germany and spoke fluent German, also won the singles title at the [[German Open Tennis Championships|German Championships]].<ref name=scotsman>{{cite news|title=Scottish Wimbledon champion that history forgot|url=http://www.scotsman.com/sport/tennis/scottish-wimbledon-champion-that-history-forgot-1-908988|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=13 July 2007}}</ref>\n\nAt the [[1900 Summer Olympics]] in Paris he won a silver medal in the [[Tennis at the 1900 Summer Olympics|men's singles event]] and a bronze medal in the [[Tennis at the 1900 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's doubles|doubles competition]] (for [[Great Britain and Ireland at the 1900 Summer Olympics|Great Britain and Ireland]]) as well as a silver medal in the [[Tennis at the 1900 Summer Olympics|mixed doubles event]] with [[H\u00e9l\u00e8ne Pr\u00e9vost]] from France. Mahony won the [[Kent Championships]] in 1899, defeating [[Wilberforce Eaves]] in the final, and in 1904, defeating [[Brame Hillyard]] in the final.<ref name=\"sports-reference\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ma/harold-mahony-1.html |title=Harold Mahony Olympic Results |publisher=sports-reference.com |accessdate=2014-01-26}}</ref>\n\nMahony was a member of the 1903 [[Great Britain Davis Cup team|British Isles Davis Cup team]] that won the against the [[United States Davis Cup team|United States]] at the [[Longwood Cricket Club]] in [[Boston]] but did not play in the event. When four-time Wimbledon champion [[Reginald Doherty]] had a shoulder injury the British team captain William Collins elected to forfeit his first match, instead of letting Mahony play, so that Doherty would be allowed to play the reverse singles match later in the event.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Randy Walker|title=Brothers Vs. Brothers In A USA Vs. Britain Davis Cup? It\u2019s Happened Before\u2026|url=http://www.worldtennismagazine.com/archives/11446|publisher=World Tennis Magazine|date=2 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nMahony was 1.91m (6&nbsp;ft 3in) tall and possessed a formidable backhand. His forehand was less notable: his fellow player, [[George Hillyard]], wrote that he \"never did acquire the right method of hitting the ball on the forehand\".<ref name=\"Grand Slam Winner\"/>\n\nMahony was killed on 27 June 1905, aged 38, in a bicycling accident while descending a steep hill near [[Caragh Lake]] in Co. Kerry.<ref name=\"Grand Slam Winner\"/><ref name=killed/>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n\n===Singles===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!style=\"width:75px\"|Outcome\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:65px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Opponent\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Score\n|-style=\"background:#cfc;\"\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner ||1896||[[1896 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]] || Grass || {{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[Wilfred Baddeley]] ||6\u20132, 6\u20138, 5\u20137, 8\u20136, 6\u20133\n|}\n\n===Doubles===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-bgcolor=\n!style=\"width:75px\"|Outcome\n!style=\"width:50px\"|Year\n!style=\"width:200px\"|Championship\n!style=\"width:65px\"|Surface\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Partner\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Opponents\n!style=\"width:180px\"|Score\n|- style=\"background:#ccf;\"\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n|1897\n|[[1897 U.S. National Championships (tennis)|U.S. Championships]]\n| Grass\n|{{flagicon|UKGBI}} [[Harold Nisbet]]\n|{{flagicon|USA|1896}} [[George Sheldon (tennis)|George Sheldon]] <br /> {{flagicon|USA|1896}} [[Leo Ware]]\n|13\u201311, 2\u20136, 7\u20139, 6\u20131, 1\u20136\n|}\n\n===Olympic medal matches===\n\n====Singles: 1 (1 silver medal)====\n{|class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n!Result\n!Year\n!width=125|Tournament\n!Surface\n!width=170|Opponent\n!width=200|Score\n|-b