lle\n| 7\u20135, 6\u20131, 4\u20136, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 71.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Sep 1901\n| South of England Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Sydney Howard Smith]]\n| 6\u20133, 7\u20139, 4\u20136, 6\u20134, 1\u20130 (ret.)\n|-  \n| 72.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Sep 1901\n| Portuguese International Championships\n| Clay\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[George Hillyard]]\n| 6\u20130, 6\u20134\n|-\n| 73.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1902\n| Leicestershire Championships<ref>{{cite web|title=LEICESTERSHIRE CH. Tournament Draw 1902|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=tournament&accion=draw&torneoSearch=LEICESTERSHIRE%20CH.&year=1902 |publisher=The Tennis Base |date=2016 |accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref> \n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Laurence Doherty]]\n| w.o.\n|-  \n| 74.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Jun 1902\n| [[Kent Championships]] \n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} George Mi\u00e9ville Simond\n| 6\u20134, 6\u20130, 6\u20133 **\n|- \n| 75.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Jun 1902\n| [[Manchester Open|Northern Championships]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Sydney Howard Smith]]\n| 7\u20135, 7\u20135, 3\u20136, 10\u20138\n|- \n| 76.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Oct 1902\n| European Championships<ref>{{cite web|last1=Archives|first1=Tennis|title=European Championship 1902|url=http://www.tennisarchives.com/voorloopfiche.php?wedstrijdvoorloopid=1033 |publisher=Tennis Archives |date=2016 |accessdate=11 December 2016}}</ref>\n| Hard (i)\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Laurence Doherty]]\n| 4\u20136, 6\u20134, 6\u20133, 6\u20131\n|-\n| 77.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Apr 1903\n| [[British Covered Court Championships]]\n| Hard (i)\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[George Hillyard]]\n| 6\u20133, 7\u20139, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 78.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1903\n| Middlesex Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Brame Hillyard]]\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20132, 6\u20133, 3\u20136, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 79.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jul 1903\n| Berkshire Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} Alfred E. Crawley\n| 6\u20133, 8\u20136\n|-  \n| 80.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1904\n| Middlesex Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} Frederick Payn\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20132, 6\u20134\n|-  \n| 81.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jun 1904\n| [[Kent Championships]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Beckenham Lawn Tennis Club: Kent Championships|url=http://www.beckenhamtennisclub.co.uk/history/kent-all-comers-championships-roll/ |publisher=Beckenham Lawn Tennis Club |date=2016|accessdate=13 December 2016}}</ref>\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Brame Hillyard]]\n| 3\u20136, 6\u20131, 6\u20132, 6\u20134\n|-  \n| 82.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jul 1904\n| North London Championships (Gipsy)\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Alfred Beamish]]\n| 6\u20131, 5\u20137, 6\u20132, 6\u20131\n|-\n| 83.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Jul 1904\n| [[Queen's Club Championships|Championship of London]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Josiah Ritchie]]\n| 6\u20133, 7\u20139, 6\u20134, 6\u20133\n|-  \n| 84.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Jul 1904\n| Berkshire Championships\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Walter Crawley]] \n| 5\u20137, 6\u20131, 6\u20134\n|-  \n| 85.\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Win\n| Aug 1904\n| Crystal Palace\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} Ernest Parton \n| 6\u20133, 6\u20132\n|-\n| 86.\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Loss\n| Jun 1905\n| [[Kent Championships]]\n| Grass\n| {{flagicon|AUS}} [[Norman Brookes]]\n| w.o.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|40em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Harold Mahony}}\n* {{ITF}}\n* {{ATP}}\n* {{Sports-reference|ma/harold-mahony-1}}\n\n{{Wimbledon men's singles champions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mahony, Harold}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1905 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:19th-century male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Scottish male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Irish male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Olympic bronze medallists for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Olympic silver medallists for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:People from County Kerry]]\n[[Category:Cycling road incident deaths]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Edinburgh]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Wimbledon champions (pre-Open Era)]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in tennis]]\n[[Category:Grand Slam (tennis) champions in men's singles]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1900 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Road incident deaths in Ireland]]\n[[Category:British male tennis players]]\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Ernest Lewis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harold_Mahony"}
{"title_page": "Half volley", "text_new": "{{About|the tennis shot|the half-volley in cricket|List of cricket terms}}\n\nA '''half volley''' in [[tennis]] is a shot that is hit immediately after the ball bounces but before it reaches the apex of its bounce. It is sometimes called an \"on the rise shot\", or \"short hop\".\n\n==Technique==\nThe player who is hitting the half volley should not take a full backswing, but should still follow through.  The [[grip (tennis)|grip]] for this shot is a standard continental. Also, staying down when hitting the shot is very important, or else it will go long. This is the basic form for the [[volley (tennis)|volley]], hence the name: half volley. The two parts of the [[tennis court]] where this shot is generally used are on the baseline and the service line.\n\n==Strategy==\nA half volley is a difficult shot to make. Often a player hits a half volley only when forced by the opponent or caught out of position. \n\nThe half-volley came to prominence in the hands of [[George Caridia]] and [[Ernest Lewis (tennis)|Ernest Lewis]] in the early 1900s.<ref>The Times, ''Borora's Record'',  23 Oct. 1935</ref>\nArguably the greatest half-volleyer in history is [[John McEnroe]]; other professionals such as [[Stefan Edberg]], [[Pete Sampras]] and [[Roger Federer]] had excellent half volleys that were used as weapons.\n\nIn his 1979 autobiography [[Jack Kramer]] devotes a page to the best tennis strokes he had ever seen.  He writes: \"HALF-VOLLEY\u2014[[Pancho Gonzales|Gonzales]] and [[Ken Rosewall|Rosewall]]. Kenny had to learn to hit a half-volley because his serve was so weak that he had to pick up shots at his feet as he came to the net.  With his great serve, I don't know why Gorgo had to hit so many half-volleys, but he sure learned how.\"\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Tennis}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KYgxZ7cuN-I Video: Half volley]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tennis box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Half Volley}}\n[[Category:Tennis shots]]\n\n\n{{tennis-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{About|the tennis shot|the half-volley in cricket|List of cricket terms}}\n\nA '''half volley''' in [[tennis]] is a shot that is hit immediately after the ball bounces but before it reaches the apex of its bounce. It is sometimes called an \"on the rise shot\", or \"short hop\".\n\n==Technique==\nThe player who is hitting the half volley should not take a full backswing, but should still follow through.  The [[grip (tennis)|grip]] for this shot is a standard continental. Also, staying down when hitting the shot is very important, or else it will go long. This is the basic form for the [[volley (tennis)|volley]], hence the name: half volley. The two parts of the [[tennis court]] where this shot is generally used are on the baseline and the service line.\n\n==Strategy==\nA half volley is a difficult shot to make. Often a player hits a half volley only when forced by the opponent or caught out of position. \n\nThe half-volley came to prominence in the hands of [[George Caridia]] and [[Ernest Lewis]] in the early 1900s.<ref>The Times, ''Borora's Record'',  23 Oct. 1935</ref>\nArguably the greatest half-volleyer in history is [[John McEnroe]]; other professionals such as [[Stefan Edberg]], [[Pete Sampras]] and [[Roger Federer]] had excellent half volleys that were used as weapons.\n\nIn his 1979 autobiography [[Jack Kramer]] devotes a page to the best tennis strokes he had ever seen.  He writes: \"HALF-VOLLEY\u2014[[Pancho Gonzales|Gonzales]] and [[Ken Rosewall|Rosewall]]. Kenny had to learn to hit a half-volley because his serve was so weak that he had to pick up shots at his feet as he came to the net.  With his great serve, I don't know why Gorgo had to hit so many half-volleys, but he sure learned how.\"\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Tennis}}\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KYgxZ7cuN-I Video: Half volley]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Tennis box}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Half Volley}}\n[[Category:Tennis shots]]\n\n\n{{tennis-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Ernest Lewis", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Half_volley"}
{"title_page": "George Hillyard", "text_new": "{{short description|British tennis player}}\n{{one source|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                              = George Hillyard\n|image                             = George Hillyard.jpg\n|caption                           = \n|fullname                          = George Whiteside Hillyard\n|country                           = {{GBR}}\n|residence                         =\n|birth_date                        = {{birth date |df=yes|1864|02|06}}\n|birth_place                       = [[Hanwell]], UK\n|death_date                        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1943|03|24|1864|02|06}}\n|death_place                       = [[Pulborough]], UK\n|height                            = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}\n|college                           =\n|turnedpro                         =\n|retired                           = \n|plays                             =\n|careerprizemoney                  =\n|tennishofyear                     =\n|tennishofid                       =\n|website                           = <!-- official web site address like this: [http://www.site.com www.site.com] -->\n|singlesrecord                     = 335/111, (75.1%) <ref name=\"The Tennis Base\">{{cite web|title=George Whiteside Hillyard: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&player_input=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=The Tennis Base|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n|singlestitles                     = 20 <ref name=\"The Tennis Base\">{{cite web|title=George Whiteside Hillyard: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&player_input=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=The Tennis Base|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n|highestsinglesranking             = No. 5 (1901<small>, Karoly Mazak</small>)<ref name=\"Mazak\">Mazak, Karoly (2010). ''The Concise History of Tennis'', p. 29.</ref>\n|currentsinglesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenresult              =\n|FrenchOpenresult                  =\n|Wimbledonresult                   = QF ([[1889 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1889]], [[1897 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1897]], [[1901 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1901]])\n|USOpenresult                      =\n|Othertournaments                  = yes\n|Olympicsresult                    = 2R ([[Tennis at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's singles|1908]])\n|doublesrecord                     =\n|doublestitles                     =\n|highestdoublesranking             =\n|currentdoublesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult       =\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult           =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult            = F ([[1889 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles|1889]], [[1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles|1890]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult               =\n|OthertournamentsDoubles           = yes\n|OlympicsDoublesresult             = '''W''' ([[Tennis at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's doubles|1908]])\n|Mixed                             = <!-- adds mixed information-->\n|mixedrecord                       =\n|mixedtitles                       =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult         =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult             =\n|WimbledonMixedresult              =\n|USOpenMixedresult                 =\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles      =\n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult         =\n| medaltemplates-expand       = yes\n| medaltemplates              =\n{{Medal|Country|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Tennis, Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1908 Summer Olympics|1908 London]]|[[Tennis at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's outdoor doubles|Outdoor doubles]]}}\n}}\n\n'''George Whiteside Hillyard''' (6 February 1864 \u2013 24 March 1943) was a male tennis player from the United Kingdom. Under his supervision as secretary of the [[All England Club]] from 1907 to 1925, the [[Wimbledon Championships]] moved to its current site at Church Road. Hillyard also excelled at cricket and golf.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nGeorge Whiteside Hillyard was born in [[Hanwell]], Middlesex on 6 February 1864, the only child of George Wright Hillyard (1817\u20131896) and his second wife Mary Mansfield (1827\u2013?). His father had been a police officer at [[Welwyn]], [[Hertfordshire]] by 1840 and later worked in the [[Nottingham]] County Jail before becoming superintendent at the [[Central London District School]] in West London in 1861. After his first wife Lucy had died in early 1862, he married Mary Mansfield in December the same year.<ref name=\"bt12\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=1\u20132 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1877, George senior sent his 13-year-old son to the [[Royal Navy]]. At first, he came to the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] as a [[Naval cadet|cadet]]. In 1879, he was promoted to [[midshipman]] and was assigned to {{HMS|Bacchante|1876|6}} which toured the colonies of the [[British Empire]] around the world from 1880 to 1882. Among his fellow midshipmen were [[Prince Albert Victor, Duke of Clarence and Avondale|Prince Albert]] and Prince George (later King [[George V]]).<ref name=\"bt56\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=5\u20136 }}</ref>\n\nHillyard resigned from the Navy with the rank of [[sub-lieutenant]] on 2 October 1885. His last posting was aboard {{HMS|Minotaur|1863|6}}.<ref name=\"bt8\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=8 }}</ref>\n\n=== Marriage and tennis career ===\nHillyard had been already introduced to tennis at the age of ten by his uncle, who had set up a [[Sphairistike]] court in 1875. However, he didn't like what he called \"pat-ball\" at first, and preferred cricket. After his Navy service, however, the rules of the game had undergone significant changes and Hillyard became attracted to it.<ref name=\"bt17\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | page=17 }}</ref> From 1887, he began to play tournaments.<ref name=\"bt55\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | page=55 }}</ref>\n\nHillyard married [[Blanche Bingley]] (1863\u20131946) in [[Greenford]] on 13 July 1887, one week after the Wimbledon final.<ref name=\"bt11\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=11 }}</ref> Blanche was the daughter of a wealthy tailoring business proprietor from London, and a successful tennis player. She had won the Wimbledon Championships in the previous year, and would win another five singles titles at Wimbledon alone until 1900. Blanche brought a considerable fortune into the marriage. Only five days after the wedding, the newly married couple competed at the Middlesex Championships at [[Chiswick Park]], and won the mixed doubles title.<ref name=\"bt11\" />\n\nIn 1889, Hillyard played the Wimbledon singles for the first time. He lost his quarter-final match against [[Harry S. Barlow|Harry Barlow]] in straight sets. He reached the doubles final twice at Wimbledon with [[Ernest Lewis (tennis)|Ernest Lewis]] in 1889 and 1890, but lost to the Renshaw brothers and [[Joshua Pim]] and [[Frank Stoker]], respectively. Alongside [[Harry Scrivener]], he won the doubles title at the [[British Covered Court Championships]] in 1890 and 1891. The following years, his focus shifted again to cricket, playing for Leicestershire, until 1896 when he won the singles, doubles, singles handicap and mixed doubles (with his wife) at [[Monte-Carlo Masters|Monte Carlo]].<ref name=\"bt6364\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=63\u201364 }}</ref> In 1897, he won the first staging of the [[German Open Tennis Championships|International German Championships]] at [[Hamburg]], beating [[George Ball-Greene]] in five sets in the final. He repeated his success at Hamburg in 1900. At Wimbledon singles, early losses enabled him to win the [[All England Plate]] in 1898, and reach the final in 1899. At the 1901 Wimbledon singles, he beat [[Laurence Doherty]] in the third round before losing in the quarter-finals to [[Arthur Gore (tennis)|Arthur Gore]].<ref name=\"bt82\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | page=82}}</ref>\n\nIn 1905, at 41 years of age, Hillyard lost the final at the [[Bad Homburg]] tournament against [[Anthony Wilding]]. He entered the Wimbledon Championships 1906, conceding a walkover to Arthur Gore. Being assigned secretary of the [[All England Club]] in 1907, he never entered the Championships again. However, he did continue to play minor tournaments such as at [[Eastbourne]], [[Yorkshire]] and Leicester until 1914. After the [[World War I|Great War]], at 55 years of age, he competed at his home tournament at Leicester and even won the mixed doubles alongside [[Gwendoline Eastlake-Smith|Gladys Lamplough]].<ref name=\"bt40\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=40 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1908, he competed at the [[1908 Summer Olympics|London Olympic Games]] and won the gold medal in doubles alongside [[Reginald Doherty]]. However, although being great fan of the Olympics in general, he was less enthusiastic about the idea of tennis being a part of it. In his book ''Forty Years of First Class Lawn Tennis'', published in 1924, he wrote: \"As for lawn tennis in conjunction with the Olympic Games, the whole thing is a inconguous farce. You could as well have Olympic cricket or Olympic golf. It is difficult to believe that players or public can treat the matter seriously or care two straws about it. Why it is wanted, or tolerated, when we already have the Davis Cup, is beyond my comprehension.\"<ref name=\"bt115\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=115}}</ref>\n\nHillyard was ranked World No. 5 for 1901 by Karoly Mazak.<ref name=\"Mazak\"/>\n\n=== Cricket ===\n[[File:LordHawkesTeaminAmerica1891.jpg|thumb|Lord Hawke's cricket team to North America in 1891/92. Hillyard is in the back row, 2nd from left.]]\nDuring his time at the Navy, Hillyard played a lot of different sports, but concentrated on cricket, and even was captain of the cricket team for two years. Afterwards, he made his first appearance for [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] in 1886. Although initially quite successful, he soon thereafter realized he had great difficulties to compete on a first-class level. Consequently, from 1887 to 1890 he virtually retired, blaming his time at the Navy which allegedly had prevented him from practising more. However, in 1891, he took cricket up again and played some first-class matches for the MCC as well as the [[Gentlemen v Players|Gentlemen Players]]. Later that year, he participated in a [[Lord Hawke's XI cricket team in North America in 1891\u201392|trip of English cricketers to North America]] led by [[Martin Hawke, 7th Baron Hawke|Lord Hawke]] in winter 1891/92. There, Hillyard played both first-class matches at [[Philadelphia]]. In 1894, Lord Hawke arranged another trip to [[Lord Hawke's XI cricket team in North America in 1894|North America]], and Hillyard was again member of the party. At Philadelphia, he played in front of an audience of 10,000.<ref name=\"bt131133\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=131\u2013133 }}</ref>\n\nUpon his return, Hillyard occasionally played cricket for another two years, making a total of 49 first-class matches in his career. After 1896, he fully committed himself to tennis.<ref name=\"bt135\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=135 }}</ref>\n\n=== Thorpe Satchville ===\nHillyard and his wife lived at [[Leicestershire]] from at least 1893. In 1896, they moved into a large house with extensive grounds at [[Thorpe Satchville]], a small village near [[Leicester]]. The mansion provided nine bedrooms as well as two tennis courts and a nine-hole golf course.<ref name=\"bt3839\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=38\u201339 }}</ref> The Hillyards frequently hosted popular house parties with tennis champions such as [[Norman Brookes]], [[Harold Mahony]], [[Anthony Wilding]], [[May Sutton]], [[Violet Pinckney]] and [[Dora Boothby]] as guests. Until 1914, almost every strong foreign player who played at Wimbledon stayed at the home of the Hillyards.<ref name=\"bt82\"/>\n\n=== Secretary of the AEC, En-tout-cas ===\nHillyard, a long-time member of the [[All England Club]] along with his wife, was its secretary from 1907 to early 1925. One of his major concerns was the upkeep of the courts, and he insisted on high standards of court maintenance. In 1910, the club purchased a motor roller for the courts in order to replace the horse roller.<ref name=\"bt97\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=97 }}</ref>\n\nWith the success of the Wimbledon tournament, the necessity to move the ground from his initial location at Worple Road to a larger site became obvious. This had been discussed as early as Hillyard became secretary in 1907, but searching for a better suitable site took time, and the outbreak of World War I further postponed the issue. From 1914 to 1918, Hillyard rejoined the Navy, leaving it with the rank of [[commander]].<ref name=\"bt122\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=122}}</ref> After the war, the decision to build a new ground was confirmed in 1919. The new site was opened at the [[1922 Wimbledon Championships]]. After the [[1919 Wimbledon Championships]], the decision to build a new ground was confirmed. As the secretary, Hillyard was probably heavily involved in the search for, and selection of the new site at Church Road, and worked together with architect [[Stanley Peach]].<ref name=\"bt99\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=99 }}</ref> The new site was opened at the [[1922 Wimbledon Championships]].\n[[File:G w hillyard, eastbourne.jpg|thumb|George Hillyard at Eastbourne]]\nBeside his secretary post, Hillyard also was an umpire at Wimbledon. From 1919 to 1932, he umpired every ladies final.<ref name=\"bt128\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=128 }}</ref>\n\nBeing passionate about building perfect grass courts, Hillyard kept thinking about how to construct an equally good all-weather court. In 1909, he met Claude Brown, a manager of a nearly bankrupt brickyard at [[Syston]] near Leicester. Hillyard had been on a tennis tour in South Africa the winter before where he had played on courts made of crushed up ant heaps. He told this story to Brown, and both developed the idea of using crushed bricks for court surface. The first court was laid out at Hillyard's home at Thorpe Satchville, and was called ''En-tout-cas'' (literally \"in all cases\") upon the idea of a guest, a French lady. Brown renamed his company after it.<ref name=\"bt120121\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=120\u2013121 }}</ref> By 1914, business boomed across England. An agent was hired for the United States market, and the company turned into a multimillion-pound business. When the Championships moved to its new site at Church Road in 1922, nine en-tout-cas courts were laid beside the grass courts. For many years, the British Junior Championships were played on en-tous-cas.<ref name=\"bt123124\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=123\u2013124 }}</ref>\n\nHillyard's relationship to the En-tout-cas company throughout the years is somewhat diffuse. Clearly, he was in the perfect position to promote the court surface, and he was certainly involved in the decision to construct en-tout-cas courts at the new Wimbledon grounds, giving them a marketing coup. In 1929, when being involved in the construction of a golf course \u2013 a job which was given to En-tout-cas on Hillyard's recommendation \u2013, he eventually disclosed that he was a director of En-tout-cas, thus obviously receiving income from the company.<ref name=\"bt155\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=155 }}</ref>\n\n=== Final years ===\nIn 1925, at an age of 61, Hillyard resigned from his position as secretary of the All England Club. In the same year, he sold his house at Thorpe Satchville, and the Hillyards moved to [[Bramfold]], [[Pulborough]], [[Sussex]]. Their new house was of similar size, and Hillyard again constructed two tennis courts,<ref name=\"bt148\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=148\u2013149 }}</ref> but began to focus on playing golf. Upon his initiative, a new golf course was completed at the West Sussex Golf Club, and opened on 8 August 1930.<ref name=\"bt155\"/>\n\nHillyard died at his home on 25 March 1943, aged 79. His wife Blanche was to survive him for three years. The couple had two children, [[Jack Hillyard|Jack]] (1890\u20131983) and Marjorie (1895\u2013?). Jack was also a tennis player, competing at Wimbledon in the 1920s and reaching the final of the [[All England Plate]] in 1924. Marjorie was mentally handicapped and stayed with her parents until the death of her mother. She spent the rest of her life at a care home in [[West Sussex]].<ref name=\"bt163\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=163 }}</ref>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n\n=== Doubles ===\n;Runners-up (2)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|width=\"200\"|'''Championship'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Partner'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Opponent in Final'''\n|width=\"160\"|'''Score in Final'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCFFCC\"\n|1889\n|[[1889 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Lewis (tennis)|Ernest Lewis]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Renshaw]] <br /> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[William Renshaw]]\n| 4\u20136, 4\u20136, 6\u20133, 6\u20130, 1\u20136\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCFFCC\"\n|1890\n|[[1890 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]]\n|  {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Lewis (tennis)|Ernest Lewis]]\n|  {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joshua Pim]] <br /> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Stoker]] \n| 0\u20136, 5\u20137, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|George Whiteside Hillyard}}\n*{{cite news | last =| first =| coauthors =| title =GW Hillyard| work =Cricket| pages =| language =| publisher =Cricinfo.com| url =http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/14830.html}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Tennis Men's Doubles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hillyard, George}}\n[[Category:1864 births]]\n[[Category:1943 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century English people]]\n[[Category:19th-century male tennis players]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:English male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Leicestershire cricketers]]\n[[Category:Marylebone Cricket Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Middlesex cricketers]]\n[[Category:English Olympic medallists]]\n[[Category:Olympic gold medallists for Great Britain]]\n[[Category:Olympic tennis players of Great Britain]]\n[[Category:People from Hanwell]]\n[[Category:People from the Borough of Melton]]\n[[Category:People from Pulborough]]\n[[Category:Tennis players at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Olympic medalists in tennis]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen cricketers]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 1908 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Gentlemen of England cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Greater London]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from Greater London]]\n[[Category:British male tennis players]]\n[[Category:Lord Hawke's XI cricketers]]\n[[Category:North v South cricketers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British tennis player}}\n{{one source|date=March 2014}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox tennis biography\n|name                              = George Hillyard\n|image                             = George Hillyard.jpg\n|caption                           = \n|fullname                          = George Whiteside Hillyard\n|country                           = {{GBR}}\n|residence                         =\n|birth_date                        = {{birth date |df=yes|1864|02|06}}\n|birth_place                       = [[Hanwell]], UK\n|death_date                        = {{death date and age|df=yes|1943|03|24|1864|02|06}}\n|death_place                       = [[Pulborough]], UK\n|height                            = {{height|ft=6|in=2}}\n|college                           =\n|turnedpro                         =\n|retired                           = \n|plays                             =\n|careerprizemoney                  =\n|tennishofyear                     =\n|tennishofid                       =\n|website                           = <!-- official web site address like this: [http://www.site.com www.site.com] -->\n|singlesrecord                     = 335/111, (75.1%) <ref name=\"The Tennis Base\">{{cite web|title=George Whiteside Hillyard: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&player_input=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=The Tennis Base|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n|singlestitles                     = 20 <ref name=\"The Tennis Base\">{{cite web|title=George Whiteside Hillyard: Career match record|url=https://app.thetennisbase.com/?enlace=playern&player_input_enc=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&player_input=HILLYARD%2C+GEORGE+WHITESIDE&sub=2#aSubmenu|website=thetennisbase.com|publisher=The Tennis Base|accessdate=19 October 2017}}</ref>\n|highestsinglesranking             = No. 5 (1901<small>, Karoly Mazak</small>)<ref name=\"Mazak\">Mazak, Karoly (2010). ''The Concise History of Tennis'', p. 29.</ref>\n|currentsinglesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenresult              =\n|FrenchOpenresult                  =\n|Wimbledonresult                   = QF ([[1889 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1889]], [[1897 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1897]], [[1901 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Singles|1901]])\n|USOpenresult                      =\n|Othertournaments                  = yes\n|Olympicsresult                    = 2R ([[Tennis at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's singles|1908]])\n|doublesrecord                     =\n|doublestitles                     =\n|highestdoublesranking             =\n|currentdoublesranking             =\n|AustralianOpenDoublesresult       =\n|FrenchOpenDoublesresult           =\n|WimbledonDoublesresult            = F ([[1889 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles|1889]], [[1890 Wimbledon Championships \u2013 Gentlemen's Doubles|1890]])\n|USOpenDoublesresult               =\n|OthertournamentsDoubles           = yes\n|OlympicsDoublesresult             = '''W''' ([[Tennis at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's doubles|1908]])\n|Mixed                             = <!-- adds mixed information-->\n|mixedrecord                       =\n|mixedtitles                       =\n|AustralianOpenMixedresult         =\n|FrenchOpenMixedresult             =\n|WimbledonMixedresult              =\n|USOpenMixedresult                 =\n|OthertournamentsMixedDoubles      =\n|OlympicMixedDoublesresult         =\n| medaltemplates-expand       = yes\n| medaltemplates              =\n{{Medal|Country|{{GBR2}}}}\n{{Medal|Sport|[[Tennis at the Summer Olympics|Tennis, Summer Olympics]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[1908 Summer Olympics|1908 London]]|[[Tennis at the 1908 Summer Olympics \u2013 Men's outdoor doubles|Outdoor doubles]]}}\n}}\n\n'''George Whiteside Hillyard''' (6 February 1864 \u2013 24 March 1943) was a male tennis player from the United Kingdom. Under his supervision as secretary of the [[All England Club]] from 1907 to 1925, the [[Wimbledon Championships]] moved to its current site at Church Road. Hillyard also excelled at cricket and golf.\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early years ===\nGeorge Whiteside Hillyard was born in [[Hanwell]], Middlesex on 6 February 1864, the only child of George Wright Hillyard (1817\u20131896) and his second wife Mary Mansfield (1827\u2013?). His father had been a police officer at [[Welwyn]], [[Hertfordshire]] by 1840 and later worked in the [[Nottingham]] County Jail before becoming superintendent at the [[Central London District School]] in West London in 1861. After his first wife Lucy had died in early 1862, he married Mary Mansfield in December the same year.<ref name=\"bt12\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=1\u20132 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1877, George senior sent his 13-year-old son to the [[Royal Navy]]. At first, he came to the [[Britannia Royal Naval College]] as a [[Naval cadet|cadet]]. In 1879, he was promoted to [[midshipman]] and was assigned to {{HMS|Bacchante|1876|6}} which toured the colonies of the [[British Empire]] around the world from 1880 to 1882. Among his fellow midshipmen were [[Prince Albert Victor, Duke of Clarence and Avondale|Prince Albert]] and Prince George (later King [[George V]]).<ref name=\"bt56\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=5\u20136 }}</ref>\n\nHillyard resigned from the Navy with the rank of [[sub-lieutenant]] on 2 October 1885. His last posting was aboard {{HMS|Minotaur|1863|6}}.<ref name=\"bt8\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=8 }}</ref>\n\n=== Marriage and tennis career ===\nHillyard had been already introduced to tennis at the age of ten by his uncle, who had set up a [[Sphairistike]] court in 1875. However, he didn't like what he called \"pat-ball\" at first, and preferred cricket. After his Navy service, however, the rules of the game had undergone significant changes and Hillyard became attracted to it.<ref name=\"bt17\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | page=17 }}</ref> From 1887, he began to play tournaments.<ref name=\"bt55\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | page=55 }}</ref>\n\nHillyard married [[Blanche Bingley]] (1863\u20131946) in [[Greenford]] on 13 July 1887, one week after the Wimbledon final.<ref name=\"bt11\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=11 }}</ref> Blanche was the daughter of a wealthy tailoring business proprietor from London, and a successful tennis player. She had won the Wimbledon Championships in the previous year, and would win another five singles titles at Wimbledon alone until 1900. Blanche brought a considerable fortune into the marriage. Only five days after the wedding, the newly married couple competed at the Middlesex Championships at [[Chiswick Park]], and won the mixed doubles title.<ref name=\"bt11\" />\n\nIn 1889, Hillyard played the Wimbledon singles for the first time. He lost his quarter-final match against [[Harry S. Barlow|Harry Barlow]] in straight sets. He reached the doubles final twice at Wimbledon with [[Ernest Lewis]] in 1889 and 1890, but lost to the Renshaw brothers and [[Joshua Pim]] and [[Frank Stoker]], respectively. Alongside [[Harry Scrivener]], he won the doubles title at the [[British Covered Court Championships]] in 1890 and 1891. The following years, his focus shifted again to cricket, playing for Leicestershire, until 1896 when he won the singles, doubles, singles handicap and mixed doubles (with his wife) at [[Monte-Carlo Masters|Monte Carlo]].<ref name=\"bt6364\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=63\u201364 }}</ref> In 1897, he won the first staging of the [[German Open Tennis Championships|International German Championships]] at [[Hamburg]], beating [[George Ball-Greene]] in five sets in the final. He repeated his success at Hamburg in 1900. At Wimbledon singles, early losses enabled him to win the [[All England Plate]] in 1898, and reach the final in 1899. At the 1901 Wimbledon singles, he beat [[Laurence Doherty]] in the third round before losing in the quarter-finals to [[Arthur Gore (tennis)|Arthur Gore]].<ref name=\"bt82\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | page=82}}</ref>\n\nIn 1905, at 41 years of age, Hillyard lost the final at the [[Bad Homburg]] tournament against [[Anthony Wilding]]. He entered the Wimbledon Championships 1906, conceding a walkover to Arthur Gore. Being assigned secretary of the [[All England Club]] in 1907, he never entered the Championships again. However, he did continue to play minor tournaments such as at [[Eastbourne]], [[Yorkshire]] and Leicester until 1914. After the [[World War I|Great War]], at 55 years of age, he competed at his home tournament at Leicester and even won the mixed doubles alongside [[Gwendoline Eastlake-Smith|Gladys Lamplough]].<ref name=\"bt40\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=40 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1908, he competed at the [[1908 Summer Olympics|London Olympic Games]] and won the gold medal in doubles alongside [[Reginald Doherty]]. However, although being great fan of the Olympics in general, he was less enthusiastic about the idea of tennis being a part of it. In his book ''Forty Years of First Class Lawn Tennis'', published in 1924, he wrote: \"As for lawn tennis in conjunction with the Olympic Games, the whole thing is a inconguous farce. You could as well have Olympic cricket or Olympic golf. It is difficult to believe that players or public can treat the matter seriously or care two straws about it. Why it is wanted, or tolerated, when we already have the Davis Cup, is beyond my comprehension.\"<ref name=\"bt115\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=115}}</ref>\n\nHillyard was ranked World No. 5 for 1901 by Karoly Mazak.<ref name=\"Mazak\"/>\n\n=== Cricket ===\n[[File:LordHawkesTeaminAmerica1891.jpg|thumb|Lord Hawke's cricket team to North America in 1891/92. Hillyard is in the back row, 2nd from left.]]\nDuring his time at the Navy, Hillyard played a lot of different sports, but concentrated on cricket, and even was captain of the cricket team for two years. Afterwards, he made his first appearance for [[Middlesex County Cricket Club|Middlesex]] against the [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] in 1886. Although initially quite successful, he soon thereafter realized he had great difficulties to compete on a first-class level. Consequently, from 1887 to 1890 he virtually retired, blaming his time at the Navy which allegedly had prevented him from practising more. However, in 1891, he took cricket up again and played some first-class matches for the MCC as well as the [[Gentlemen v Players|Gentlemen Players]]. Later that year, he participated in a [[Lord Hawke's XI cricket team in North America in 1891\u201392|trip of English cricketers to North America]] led by [[Martin Hawke, 7th Baron Hawke|Lord Hawke]] in winter 1891/92. There, Hillyard played both first-class matches at [[Philadelphia]]. In 1894, Lord Hawke arranged another trip to [[Lord Hawke's XI cricket team in North America in 1894|North America]], and Hillyard was again member of the party. At Philadelphia, he played in front of an audience of 10,000.<ref name=\"bt131133\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=131\u2013133 }}</ref>\n\nUpon his return, Hillyard occasionally played cricket for another two years, making a total of 49 first-class matches in his career. After 1896, he fully committed himself to tennis.<ref name=\"bt135\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=135 }}</ref>\n\n=== Thorpe Satchville ===\nHillyard and his wife lived at [[Leicestershire]] from at least 1893. In 1896, they moved into a large house with extensive grounds at [[Thorpe Satchville]], a small village near [[Leicester]]. The mansion provided nine bedrooms as well as two tennis courts and a nine-hole golf course.<ref name=\"bt3839\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=38\u201339 }}</ref> The Hillyards frequently hosted popular house parties with tennis champions such as [[Norman Brookes]], [[Harold Mahony]], [[Anthony Wilding]], [[May Sutton]], [[Violet Pinckney]] and [[Dora Boothby]] as guests. Until 1914, almost every strong foreign player who played at Wimbledon stayed at the home of the Hillyards.<ref name=\"bt82\"/>\n\n=== Secretary of the AEC, En-tout-cas ===\nHillyard, a long-time member of the [[All England Club]] along with his wife, was its secretary from 1907 to early 1925. One of his major concerns was the upkeep of the courts, and he insisted on high standards of court maintenance. In 1910, the club purchased a motor roller for the courts in order to replace the horse roller.<ref name=\"bt97\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=97 }}</ref>\n\nWith the success of the Wimbledon tournament, the necessity to move the ground from his initial location at Worple Road to a larger site became obvious. This had been discussed as early as Hillyard became secretary in 1907, but searching for a better suitable site took time, and the outbreak of World War I further postponed the issue. From 1914 to 1918, Hillyard rejoined the Navy, leaving it with the rank of [[commander]].<ref name=\"bt122\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=122}}</ref> After the war, the decision to build a new ground was confirmed in 1919. The new site was opened at the [[1922 Wimbledon Championships]]. After the [[1919 Wimbledon Championships]], the decision to build a new ground was confirmed. As the secretary, Hillyard was probably heavily involved in the search for, and selection of the new site at Church Road, and worked together with architect [[Stanley Peach]].<ref name=\"bt99\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=99 }}</ref> The new site was opened at the [[1922 Wimbledon Championships]].\n[[File:G w hillyard, eastbourne.jpg|thumb|George Hillyard at Eastbourne]]\nBeside his secretary post, Hillyard also was an umpire at Wimbledon. From 1919 to 1932, he umpired every ladies final.<ref name=\"bt128\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=128 }}</ref>\n\nBeing passionate about building perfect grass courts, Hillyard kept thinking about how to construct an equally good all-weather court. In 1909, he met Claude Brown, a manager of a nearly bankrupt brickyard at [[Syston]] near Leicester. Hillyard had been on a tennis tour in South Africa the winter before where he had played on courts made of crushed up ant heaps. He told this story to Brown, and both developed the idea of using crushed bricks for court surface. The first court was laid out at Hillyard's home at Thorpe Satchville, and was called ''En-tout-cas'' (literally \"in all cases\") upon the idea of a guest, a French lady. Brown renamed his company after it.<ref name=\"bt120121\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=120\u2013121 }}</ref> By 1914, business boomed across England. An agent was hired for the United States market, and the company turned into a multimillion-pound business. When the Championships moved to its new site at Church Road in 1922, nine en-tout-cas courts were laid beside the grass courts. For many years, the British Junior Championships were played on en-tous-cas.<ref name=\"bt123124\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=123\u2013124 }}</ref>\n\nHillyard's relationship to the En-tout-cas company throughout the years is somewhat diffuse. Clearly, he was in the perfect position to promote the court surface, and he was certainly involved in the decision to construct en-tout-cas courts at the new Wimbledon grounds, giving them a marketing coup. In 1929, when being involved in the construction of a golf course \u2013 a job which was given to En-tout-cas on Hillyard's recommendation \u2013, he eventually disclosed that he was a director of En-tout-cas, thus obviously receiving income from the company.<ref name=\"bt155\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=155 }}</ref>\n\n=== Final years ===\nIn 1925, at an age of 61, Hillyard resigned from his position as secretary of the All England Club. In the same year, he sold his house at Thorpe Satchville, and the Hillyards moved to [[Bramfold]], [[Pulborough]], [[Sussex]]. Their new house was of similar size, and Hillyard again constructed two tennis courts,<ref name=\"bt148\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=148\u2013149 }}</ref> but began to focus on playing golf. Upon his initiative, a new golf course was completed at the West Sussex Golf Club, and opened on 8 August 1930.<ref name=\"bt155\"/>\n\nHillyard died at his home on 25 March 1943, aged 79. His wife Blanche was to survive him for three years. The couple had two children, [[Jack Hillyard|Jack]] (1890\u20131983) and Marjorie (1895\u2013?). Jack was also a tennis player, competing at Wimbledon in the 1920s and reaching the final of the [[All England Plate]] in 1924. Marjorie was mentally handicapped and stayed with her parents until the death of her mother. She spent the rest of her life at a care home in [[West Sussex]].<ref name=\"bt163\">{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490 | pages=163 }}</ref>\n\n==Grand Slam finals==\n\n=== Doubles ===\n;Runners-up (2)\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|width=\"200\"|'''Championship'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Partner'''\n|width=\"180\"|'''Opponent in Final'''\n|width=\"160\"|'''Score in Final'''\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCFFCC\"\n|1889\n|[[1889 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Lewis]]\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Renshaw]] <br /> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[William Renshaw]]\n| 4\u20136, 4\u20136, 6\u20133, 6\u20130, 1\u20136\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCFFCC\"\n|1890\n|[[1890 Wimbledon Championships|Wimbledon Championships]]\n|  {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Ernest Lewis]]\n|  {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Joshua Pim]] <br /> {{flagicon|GBR}} [[Frank Stoker]] \n| 0\u20136, 5\u20137, 4\u20136\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Commons category|George Whiteside Hillyard}}\n*{{cite news | last =| first =| coauthors =| title =GW Hillyard| work =Cricket| pages =| language =| publisher =Cricinfo.com| url =http://content-uk.cricinfo.com/england/content/player/14830.html}}\n*{{cite book |last=Tarran |first=Bruce |date=2013 |title=George Hillyard: The Man Who Moved Wimbledon |location=Kibworth Beauchamp |publisher=Matador |isbn=978-1780885490}}\n\n{{Footer Olympic Champions Tennis Men's Doubles}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hillyard, George}}\n[[Ca